# Oddbits "bit" architecture

A **bit** is a self-contained tool. `packages/imagebits` + `apps/web/src/components/imagebits.ts` is the **canonical reference**.

## Project pledges (non-negotiable)

Bits inherit these constraints from the project:

- MIT licensed, free, no ads, no rate limits.
- **No server-side processing.** Bits run in the browser, in Node, or via the CLI on the user's machine.
- **No tracking, no telemetry, no analytics, no data collection.**
- **No accounts, no API keys, no BYOK surfaces.** If a bit needs a model, it runs locally (e.g. WASM/ONNX via transformers.js).
- **Minimal dependencies.** Vanilla TypeScript; no UI frameworks for libraries or the desktop shell.
- **Credit your sources.** Bundled fonts/assets and meaningful deps go in `CREDITS.md` in the same PR.

If a request would violate any of these, surface it before proceeding. Full version in `AGENTS.md` at the repo root.

## Bit shape variants — pick the smallest that fits

Not every bit needs a desktop UI. The four supported shapes:

| Shape | Surfaces | Use when |
|---|---|---|
| `lib-only` | `packages/{name}bits/` library + tests | Pure code helper, never user-facing |
| `lib + cli` | adds `bin` entry + `cli.ts` + CLI tests | Tool that's most useful from a terminal (calculators, encoders, beautifiers) |
| `lib + cli + minimal-web` | adds desktop icon + a minimal info window (description, version, `Source` + `Use in your project` buttons; **no** `<odd-…>`, **no** workshop) | CLI-first bit that just needs a desktop presence linking to its npx usage |
| `lib + cli + full-web` | full four-surface desktop pattern (canonical: `imagebits`) | Bit that benefits from drag-in / tweak / get-output interaction |

Naming: package names always end in `bits` and live under the `@oddbits/` npm scope (`@oddbits/imagebits`, `@oddbits/colorbits`, `@oddbits/clipbits`). Custom-element tag follows `<odd-{name}bits>`.

## The four surfaces (full-web shape)

The full pattern has these layers:

1. **Desktop icon** — entry on the faux-desktop, `index.html` → `.desktop-icons`.
2. **Desktop window** — small intro window with description + embedded `<odd-{name}bits>` web component + `.bit-actions` row (`Source` link + `How To` button).
3. **Workshop dialog** — modal-style `.window`, `position: fixed`, `z-index: 400`, **portaled to `document.body`** for the actual work.
4. **Alerts & inline help** — `.alert-modal-*` for confirms/notices; `.popover` + `.help-trigger` for inline help.

For the `minimal-web` shape, only #1 and #2 apply — the desktop window has the description and links but no `<odd-…>` element and no workshop. No `BitElement` subclass is required.

## Plugin registry vs desktop registry

`@oddbits/core` exposes `BitPlugin` + `registerBit()`. That registry is for **code-level callers** — Node scripts, third-party hosts that want to plug bits into their own pipelines. The desktop UI does **not** discover bits through it; `apps/web/src/main.ts` imports each web component statically. You do **not** need to call `registerBit()` to make a desktop bit work.

## Reuse the design system, never duplicate

The "DESIGN SYSTEM" section at the top of `apps/web/src/styles.css` defines every universal control. Use these exact classes:

- Buttons: `button` / `.btn-3d` (default), `.btn-secondary` (low-emphasis/destructive), `.window-btn` (24×24 chrome), `.win-link-btn` (anchor styled as button).
- Inputs: `input`, `select`, `textarea`, `input[type="range"]` — already styled.
- Help popovers: `.popover-anchor` + `.help-trigger` + `.popover`.
- Combo buttons: `.combo-button-group` + `.combo-main-btn` + `.combo-caret-btn` + `.combo-dropdown` + `.combo-item`.
- Alert/confirm dialogs: `.alert-modal-backdrop` + `.alert-modal` + `.alert-modal-icon/title/message/actions`.

If you find yourself adding a `padding`, `background`, or `border` to a button/input/slider/dialog, **stop** — the design system already covers it. Add a layout-only override only if absolutely necessary, scoped to your component.

## Web component pattern

**Always extend `BitElement`** (`apps/web/src/bits/BitElement.ts`). It provides ALL of the generic infrastructure: workshop dialog open/close/drag/resize/portal, help dialog, alert/confirm modal, escape priority chain, raise-z on click, document-mousedown chain, dirty-close guard, and cleanup.

In `apps/web/src/components/{name}bits.ts`:

```ts
import { BitElement } from '../bits/BitElement';

export class NameBitsElement extends BitElement {
  protected renderShell(): string { return `…shell + workshop + help + alert markup…`; }
  protected initializeBitElements(): void { /* query bit-specific refs */ }
  protected attachBitListeners(): void { /* wire bit-specific events */ }
  protected isWorkshopDirty(): boolean { /* return true if there's unsaved work */ }
  protected resetWorkshopState(): void { /* reset state when workshop closes */ }

  // Optional overrides:
  protected getHostWindowSelector() { return '#window-namebits'; }
  protected getVersion() { return VERSION; } // from `@oddbits/{name}bits`
  protected onAcceptConfirmClose() { /* set abort flags before closeWorkshop() */ }
  protected handleEscapePopover() { /* return true to claim Escape */ return false; }
  protected onDocumentMouseDownBit(e: MouseEvent) { /* dismiss bit popovers on outside click */ }
  protected onDisconnect() { /* revoke object URLs */ }
}

customElements.define('odd-namebits', NameBitsElement);
```

Then `import './components/{name}bits';` in `src/main.ts`.

Required CSS classes in your `renderShell()` HTML — `BitElement` discovers elements by these:

- `.bit-shell` — root container the workshop returns to on close
- `.bit-workshop` — workshop dialog (combine with `.window`)
- `.bit-workshop-close` — workshop X button
- `.bit-drag-handle` — workshop titlebar (drag region)
- `.bit-help-dialog` — help dialog (optional; combine with `.window`)
- `.bit-help-close` — help dialog X button (optional)

**Help dialog copy:** keep How To content **short** and **high-level** (in-app orientation). Match length/shape guidance in `apps/web/UI_THEME.md` (**Help dialog — content & length**). Link to `packages/{name}bits/README.md` on GitHub for full CLI/API docs — do not paste the README into the dialog.
- `.bit-confirm-backdrop` — alert/confirm modal backdrop (optional)
- `.bit-confirm-cancel` / `.bit-confirm-accept` — confirm buttons (optional)

Required CSS class on the host desktop window (in `index.html`):

- `.bit-help-launch` — buttons that open the help dialog (optional)
- `[data-bit-version]` — empty `<span>` inside the host titlebar that `BitElement` fills with `getVersion()` (optional, recommended)

Behaviors `BitElement` gives you for free:

- **Host styling inheritance** — auto-copies the host desktop window's `.pop-*` tint and `.window-title-icon` onto the workshop + help dialog. Drop the `.pop-*` class and a `<span class="window-title-icon">…</span>` on the `#window-{name}bits` element in `index.html` and the dialogs match without extra wiring.
- **Live version in titlebar** — override `getVersion()` to return the underlying npm package's `VERSION` export (kept in sync by release-please via `extra-files`); `BitElement` writes it into any `[data-bit-version]` placeholder inside the host titlebar. Markup pattern: `…NameBits_v<span data-bit-version>0.0.0</span>.exe`.
- **Portal modals to `document.body`** — fixed positioning escapes ancestor `transform`/stacking contexts.
- **Escape priority**: alert → bit popover (`handleEscapePopover()`) → help → workshop. First open layer wins.
- **Raise-z on click**: bumps a shared static `dialogZ` counter so newly clicked dialogs come forward.
- **Dirty-close guard**: workshop X + Escape → `requestCloseWorkshop()` → confirm modal → accept calls `onAcceptConfirmClose()` (your abort flags) then `closeWorkshop()` → `resetWorkshopState()` (your bit cleanup).
- **Cleanup on disconnect**: removes portaled elements + listeners; you only have to revoke `URL.createObjectURL` references in `onDisconnect()`.

## Quick checklist

- [ ] `packages/{name}bits/` headless lib (mirror `packages/imagebits`)
- [ ] `packages/{name}bits/src/index.ts` exports `VERSION` with the `// x-release-please-version` marker
- [ ] `release-please-config.json` lists the new package + `extra-files` entry for `src/index.ts`
- [ ] `apps/web/src/components/{name}bits.ts` web component (override `getVersion()` to return `VERSION`)
- [ ] Desktop icon in `index.html` with `data-target="window-{name}bits"`
- [ ] Desktop window `id="window-{name}bits"` + intro + `<odd-{name}bits>` + `.bit-actions`, titlebar uses `<span data-bit-version>0.0.0</span>` placeholder
- [ ] `import './components/{name}bits';` in `src/main.ts`
- [ ] Reused design system classes (no duplicate styling)
- [ ] Modals portaled to `document.body`
- [ ] Dirty-close confirm if workshop has unsaved work
- [ ] Cleanup in `disconnectedCallback`

